Cell[CellGroupData[{
Cell["Model V1 - Self-Balancing Tail with Variable Length", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.929354612578005*^9, 3.929354616192994*^9}, {
  3.929355210549653*^9, 3.9293552190879917`*^9}, {3.9918429510719347`*^9, 
  3.991842958992612*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"067356c3-28ca-4144-be02-\
7957e03610f3"],

Cell["\<\
Before changing the angle of the tail or adding more joints, we need to \
understand how balance works. In physics, balance is achieved by having a net \
torque of zero in our system. In this case, our system is defined as the \
following: with a center of mass for the tail offset by a distance and a \
center of mass for the head offset by a distance and height. For all \
calculations, we will use SI units.

From this setup, we must derive an equation that can be used. In this setup, \
the six main variables are:
m_head - the mass of the head.
d_head - the horizontal distance from the point mass of the head to the body.
h_head - the vertical distance from the point mass of the head to the body.

m_tail - the mass of the head.
d_tail - the horizontal distance from the point mass of the head to the body. \
It\[CloseCurlyQuote]s important to note that the center of mass is this value \
divided by two as it\[CloseCurlyQuote]s not a point mass.
h_tail - the vertical distance from the point mass of the head to the body.

However, our monkey will not always be standing. Thus, we need to factor in a \
7th variable, \[Theta]_head. In our diagram, \[Theta]_head looks like this:


With the variables setup, we can begin calculations. Because there are only \
two masses in the system, the head and the tail, the torque equation looks \
like this: \|01d70f_head = \|01d70f_tail
Substituting in the equation that torque is \|01d70f = F*r*sin(\[Theta]), we \
can calculate our radius (r) as this:
r_tail = sqrt((d_tail/2)^2+h_tail^2)
r_head = sqrt(d_head^2+h_head^2)

Calculating 

If we changed \[Theta]_tail, the system would just fall. To accommodate for \
this, we must make one or more of the six variables unknown such that the \
model can automatically adjust it to keep the torques in equilibrium. In this \
example, we will solve for d_tail as our unknown variable.\
\>", "Text",
